text: First Stereoselective Total Synthesis of a Dimeric Naphthoquinonopyrano-g-lactone: (+)-g-Actinorhodin Markus Neumeyer and Reinhard Br(cid:2)ckner* Abstract: We have accomplished the first total synthesis of an isomerically pure naphthoquinonopyrano-g-lactone dimer, g-actinorhodin, in eleven steps. Two steps exploit pairs of peri-MeO groups as unusual selectivity controls. The respective MeO groups convey the steric bulk of a bromo or iodo substituent located ortho to one MeO group as steric hindrance into the vicinity of the second MeO group. This relay effect was indispensable for exerting regiocontrol in an aromatic bromi- nation and diastereocontrol in an oxa-Pictet–Spengler cycliza- tion. The absolute configuration of our target compound was established in an asymmetric Sharpless dihydroxylation of a b,g-unsaturated ester, which was synthesized in a Heck coupling of a bromoiodonaphthalene with ethyl vinylacetate. The dihydroxylation provided the g-hydroxylactone moiety of the bromonaphthalene that was used as the substrate in the oxa- Pictet–Spengler cyclization. Dimerization to the core of g-actinorhodin occurred by two Suzuki couplings. Naphthoquinonopyrano-g-lactone natural products with

annulated g-lactone rings (Figure 1) have attracted the attention of pharmacologists as well as chemists. These compounds act against Gram-positive and -negative bacteria as well as against fungi.[1] Some derivatives inhibit a serine/ threonine kinase associated with malignant tumors.[2] More- over, they are challenging targets for synthesis.[3] The mono- (+)-kalafungin naphthoquinonopyrano-g-lactones meric (1),[4, 5] (+)-frenolicin B (2),[6, 4c, 5c, 7] and ((cid:2))-griseusin A (3)[8, 9] have been obtained by total synthesis. Much less is known about the synthesis of naturally occurring naphtho- quinonopyrano-g-lactone dimers. For example, the combined synthetic efforts towards ((cid:2))-crisamycin A (7 a)[10] ended prematurely with the synthesis of dimeric precursors,[11] a 1:1 mixture—not referred to as such by the authors—of rac-crisamycin A (7 b) and meso-crisamycin A (8 b),[12] or the synthesis of a compound that resisted demethylation in what would have been the final step.[13] Endeavors towards g-actinorhodin (5) and actinorhodin (6) came to a halt at the stage of precursors,[14] “half-sized molecules”,[15] or ear- lier.[16] In fact, our total synthesis of g-actinorhodin (5) described in the following is the very first synthesis of Angew. g-Actinorhodin (5) was isolated from Streptomyces coeli- color also by Brockmann and co-workers.[30] Its structure was published as shown in Figure 1[34] (albeit without the position of the naphthazarin–naphthazarin bond) yet also with swap- ped hydroquinone/quinone pairs.[28b] These structures resem- ble formula 6 of actinorhodin[29] and its tautomer,[28] respec- tively. The difference is that g-actinorhodin (henceforth represented by 5) is a dilactone and actinorhodin (6) is a diacid. The 1H NMR signals of the dihydropyranolactone moiety of g-actinorhodin tetraacetate equal[30] those of its in granaticin B.[35] A derivative thereof was counterpart characterized by X-ray diffraction.[35b] Accordingly, the dihy- dropyranolactone be 3a,5trans,3a,11bcis-configured.[30] The absolute configuration of g-actinorhodin (5) was determined by CD[28b] and ORD spectroscopy.[30, 28b] However, how they relate to the config- urations shown in Ref. [28b, 34] is unclear. The naphthazarin– naphthazarin bond in g-actinorhodin (5) was not localized by first principles. Its position was assigned based on the plausibility (at the time) or likelihood (today)[36] of actino- rhodin (6) being a biosynthetic precursor of g-actinorhodin (5) and thereby defining it constitutionally as well as configurationally.[37] We intended to synthesize g-actinorhodin (5) by a non- biomimetic route (Scheme 1) that involves the late-stage reductive dimerization of an aryl halide (11). This halide is related to halogen-free naphthoquinonopyrano-g-lactones,

Scheme 1. Retrosynthesis of g-actinorhodin with a Sharpless asymmet- ric dihydroxylation (SAD) as a key step for establishing the lactone motif. which we had prepared in earlier studies.[5b, 38] Accordingly, 11 should be reached analogously, that is, by a dihydropyran- forming oxa-Pictet–Spengler cyclization[39] of b-hydroxy-g- lactone 12, which itself should result from an asymmetric dihydroxylation of the trans-configured b,g-unsaturated ester 15.[40] Such esters can be obtained by the Heck coupling of an aryl halide and an alkyl 2-vinylacetate.[41] We intended to use naphthalene dihalides 14 as substrates. They should result from halogenations of tetramethoxynaphthalene 13.[42] For instance, NBS and compound 13 in CCl4 at reflux afford naphthalene dibromide 14 a in 88 % yield[43] (Scheme 2). However, this yield could be improved to 82 % when 13 was brominated with NBS at room temperature in DMF. As in CCl4,[43] the regiocontrol was perfect so that iso-14 a was not formed.

Naphthalene dibromide 14 a underwent an aromatic Finkelstein reaction[44] in dioxane at reflux over 3 days (Scheme 2), which furnished naphthalene diiodide 14 b in 65 % yield. Attempts to shorten this access by exposing tetramethoxynaphthalene 13[42] to 2.2 equiv of nBuLi and TMEDA[45] and quenching the supposed intermediate dili- thio-13 with iodine failed. However, upon employing half as much nBuLi and TMEDA, tetramethoxynaphthalene 13 was converted into monolithio-13. Iodonaphthalene 16 c (65 % yield) was obtained upon iodine addition. Treatment with NBS in DMF, but not in CCl4, CH2Cl2, or acetonitrile, led to the mixed dihalide 14 c in 83 % yield, again with perfect regiocontrol, that is, without iso-14 c. We wondered whether bis(methylenedioxy)-substituted naphthalene 17[42] (Scheme 2), an analogue and plausible synthetic equivalent of tetramethoxynaphthalene 13,[42] would be a better starting material for our endeavor. However, 17 evaded not only attempted dilithiations (like 13) but dibro- minations, too (unlike 13). Dilithiation attempts with 17 gave Angew. Chem. Int. Ed. 2017, 56, 1 – 7

no interpretable result. A 2:1 mixture of NBS and 17 in DMF delivered an inseparable 19:38:34:9 mixture of four products. According to GC-MS and 1H NMR analysis (300 MHz, CDCl3), two unassigned dibromonaphthalenes 19 and iso-19, and tribro- monaphthalene 20, respectively. This result is in sharp contrast to the chemo- and regioselectivity of the dibromina- tion of tetramethoxynaphthalene 13. Whence the difference? The carbon–halogen bonds in aryl bromide 16 a and aryl iodide 16 c exert a remote substituent effect during the bromination of these substrates (Figure 2). We suggest that Figure 2. A remote, yet relayed steric effect for rationalizing regiocon- trol during the brominations of 16 a to 14 a (step 2 of the dibromina- tion 13!14 a) and of 16 c to 14 c in Scheme 3. this effect is steric in nature:[46] The 2–halogen bond forces the 1-O(cid:2)Me and 8-O(cid:2)Me bonds to point away from itself and away from one another. If, in addition, the C(cid:2)+O(cid:2)C(cid:2)C(cid:2)C(cid:2) O(cid:2)C moiety ortho to the sp3-hybridized carbon atom in the Wheland complex is planar for maximum resonance stabili- zation, the 6-brominated Wheland complexes pre-14 c and pre-14 a should be less sterically hindered than the respective 7-brominated isomers pre-iso-14 c and pre-iso-14 a. If, more- over, the naphthalene 2-halides 16 a and 16 c react with NBS in accordance with the Hammond postulate, the C6 position should be brominated faster than the C7 position, which is what we observed.

Next, we studied monocouplings of naphthalene dibro- mide 14 a, diiodide 14 b, and bromide/iodide 14 c with ethyl 2-vinylacetate (Scheme 3). Heck couplings with this olefin are known.[41] Employing Pd(OAc)2/P(oTol)3 [41b] as the precata- lyst, we hoped for enough delay between the desired first and the unintended second Heck coupling of dihalides 14 a–14 c. However, dibromide 14 a and diiodide 14 b underwent the Heck couplings without much kinetic differentiation: The dibromide gave 34 % of the monocoupled and 11 % of the biscoupled product. Similarly, the diiodide led to 30 % monocoupling and 26 % biscoupling. In contrast, subjecting monoiodonaphthalene 14 c and ethyl 2-vinylacetate to the Heck conditions functionalized only the C(cid:2)I bond. This produced a 90:10 mixture of the bromine-containing trans- configured esters 21 (b,g-unsaturated, desired) and 21’ (a,b- unsaturated, undesired) in 74 % yield. Angew. Chem. Int. Sharpless asymmetric dihydroxylation (SAD) of the mixture of enoate isomers 21 and 21’ under buffered conditions[47] gave 62 % of b-hydroxy-g-lactone 24 with high enantiocontrol as predicted[40] (99.3 % ee; Scheme 4). The (b-naphthyl)ethanol moiety formed a hemiacetal with acet- aldehyde, which underwent an oxa-Pictet–Spengler cycliza- tion.[39] This led to a 90:10 mixture of the naphthohydroqui- nonopyrano-g-lactones 26 and epi-26. The former compound was the desired one and could be purified by recrystalliza- tion.[48] The 90:10 diastereoselectivity of this reaction con- trasts with the inverse 67:33 diastereoselectivity of the oxa- Pictet–Spengler cyclization of 25[42] and acetaldehyde to give epi-27 and 27.[49] The respective substrates are very similar because 24 represents 6’-bromo-25. A remote, but relayed steric effect, akin to the remote halogen effects in the naphthalene-based Wheland complexes pre-14 a and pre-14 c, might cause the difference: the C6’(cid:2)Br bond in 24 should push the methoxy groups at C5’ and C4’ closer to the cyclization site (C3’) than in the bromine-free substrate 24. This establishes distinct neighborhoods.[50] We dimerized the monomeric structure 26 into a precursor of g-actinorhodin (5), as shown in Scheme 5, top. In spite of a rec- ommendation to do the contrary,[54] we employed bis(pinaco- lato)diboron, CsF, and [PdCl2(dppf)] to bring about this reaction, and obtained bisnaphthalene 29 (52 %, > 99 % ee). Oxidation with (NH4)2[Ce(NO3)6] delivered a 28:44:28 mix- ture of the constitutionally isomeric bis(8,8’-naphthoqui- none)s 30, 31, and 32 in 98 % yield (crude product). Compounds 30 and 31 were isolated and structurally charac- terized by 1D, HMBC, and NOESY NMR spectroscopy. The 13C NMR resonances (126 MHz, CDCl3) of the oxygenated sp2-hybridized carbon atoms in the quinone motif appear approximately 25 ppm downfield of those in the hydro- quinone diether motif. This ordering allowed to conclude that the C8(cid:2)C8’ bond links two hydroquinone diether moieties in isomer 30, one quinone and one hydroquinone diether in 31, and two quinones in 32. The mixture of compounds 30–32 was subjected to demethylation with AlCl3 in CH2Cl2 (Scheme 5). Extractive workup and chromatography on deactivated silica gel suf- fered from near-insolubility and near-inseparability of our target molecule from compounds that we considered to be MeO-containing byproducts. Approximately 5 % of one naphthoquinonopyrano-g-lactone dimer were finally isolated. Its 1H NMR spectrum (500 MHz, CDCl3) matched that of g-actinorhodin (5)[55] without excluding the equally publish- (cid:2) 2017 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim

ed[28b] tautomeric structure ditauto-5. In line with both views, there were fewer 13C NMR resonances[56] (126 MHz, CDCl3) than expected for the unsymmetric structure monotauto-5. Characteristic HMBC cross-peaks allowed the quinone moiety to be located next to the dihydropyran ring.[57] They also place the hydroquinone moiety next to the biaryl bond.[57] Both observations confirm that this compound has structure 5[27] and not structure ditauto-5.[28b] For stereochemical characterization we also studied 5 and its antipode by chiroptical spectroscopy (Figure 3). The CD spectra of synthetic 5 (Figure 3, left) and natural g-actino- rhodin[28b] are very similar. The likeness of the respective ORD spectra is equally clear (synthetic: Figure 3, right; Figure 3. Ed. 2017, 56, 1 – 7 natural: Ref. [28b, 30]). The absolute configuration of g-actinorhodin[28b] has thus been confirmed by total synthesis. To be absolutely certain, synthetic 5 was esterified to tetraacetate 33 (Scheme 5, bottom left). Its structure was determined by NMR spectroscopy as described for 5 (see above) with the same rigor.[57, 58] The 1H and 13C NMR data (500 and 126 MHz, respectively, CDCl3) of our synthetic sample of 33 agree well[59] with those of a sample of 33 derived from natural g-actinorhodin.[30, 28b] Moreover, we recorded the same IR absorptions of 33 as described.[30]

In conclusion, we have achieved the first total synthesis of a dimeric naphthoquinonopyrano-g-lactone natural product, g-actinorhodin, in eleven steps. Iodine and bromine substitu- ents four to five carbon centers away from the reaction site controlled the chemo- and diastereoselectivity of SEAr reactions of polysubstituted naphthalenes by a relay effect involving two MeO groups.
